%I A046160 #17 Mar 10 2026 20:47:09
%S A046160 2,5,6,9,11,14,15,18,21,23,27,30,33
%N A046160 Bends of spheres in Soddy's bowl of integers, having their center not in the plane.
%H A046160 Frederick Soddy, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1038/139077a0">The Bowl of Integers and the Hexlet</a>, Nature 139, 77-79, 1937 [<a href="https://scispace.com/pdf/the-bowl-of-integers-and-the-hexlet-2g1v1j2x4s.pdf">Accessible copy</a>]
%H A046160 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/BowlofIntegers.html">Bowl of Integers.</a>
%e A046160 a(1) = 2 is the bend of the two "initial" spheres of radius 1/2, centered in (0, 0, +- 0.5), touching each other at the origin, and the unit sphere in (0, 0, +-1). Next there are six spheres of radius 1/3, centered in the plane, each of which touches its two neighbor spheres with bend 3, and also the two spheres of bend 2, and also the outer sphere of bend -1. Since their center is on the plane, their bend is not listed here.
%e A046160 a(2) = 5 is the bend of the two times six spheres that can be filled in between the spheres of bend 2 and the above mentioned spheres of bend 3, six above and six below the plane z=0. Since their center is not in the plane, their bend is again listed here.
%Y A046160 Cf. A046159 (bends of spheres centered on the plane).
%Y A046160 Cf. A045506 (list of all bends: -1, 2, 3, 5, ...).
%K A046160 nonn,more,nice,changed
%O A046160 1,1
%A A046160 _Eric W. Weisstein_
